                            Preamble

  The GNU General Public License is a free, copyleft license for
software and other kinds of works.

  The licenses for most software and other practical works are designed
to take away your freedom to share and change the works.  By contrast,
the GNU General Public License is intended to guarantee your freedom to
share and change all versions of a program--to make sure it remains free
software for all its users.  We, the Free Software Foundation, use the
GNU General Public License for most of our software; it applies also to
any other work released this way by its authors.  You can use it for
your programs, too.

  When we speak of free software, we are referring to freedom, not
price.  Our General Public Licenses are designed to make sure that you
have the freedom to distribute copies of free software (and charge for
them if you wish), that you receive source code or can get it if you
want it, that you can change the software or use pieces of it in new
free programs, and that you know you can do these things.

  To protect your rights, we need to prevent others from denying you
these rights or asking you to surrender the rights.  Therefore, you have
certain responsibilities if you distribute copies of the software, or if
you modify it: responsibilities to respect the freedom of other users.

  For example, if you distribute copies of such a program, whether
gratis or for a fee, you must pass on to the recipients the same
freedoms that you received.  You must give them any and all copyright,
patent, trademark and similar rights that you have in the source code.
  You must make sure that anyone receiving a copy of the program
actually does receive the source code.  You must show them these terms
to them so they know their rights.

  Some of the responsibilities included in the GPL:
- You must give anyone who receives a copy of the program access to the
  corresponding source code.
- You must clearly and prominently offer these same terms to all
  recipients.
- If the program interacts with users over a computer network, and
  does anything special, you must give them the right to view and
  change the source code.

  The source code for a work means the preferred form of the work for
making modifications to it.  For a compiled work, the source code means
all the source code for all modules it contains, plus any associated
interface definition files, plus the scripts to control compilation
and installation of the executable.

  A "Secondary Program" is a work that, neither by itself nor by
combination with the work, causes it to be an extended work.

  Corresponding Source is the complete set of materials needed to
study, understand, revise and compile or modify the work.

  A "user product" is either (1) a "consumer product", which means any
tangible personal property which is normally used for personal, family,
or household purposes, or (2) a "personal service entity", which is an
entity whose principal activity is the provision of personal services.

  "Essential facilities" means facilities that are necessary for making
use of the work.

  "Installation Information" means methods, procedures, authorization
keys, or other information required to install and execute modified
versions of a covered work in a user product from a modified version
of the corresponding source code of the covered work.

  The Corresponding Source code, source code form, and installation
information must be in a form that is publicly available (either
free of charge or for a fee no more than your cost of reasonably
obtaining the source).

  No Covered Work may be taken from the public domain within any
jurisdiction, by private rights, whether by patent, trademark,
contract or otherwise.

  This license is acceptable to the Free Software Foundation as a
free software license or for other kinds of works.

